The Roc Road

The Roc Road is not merely a path between places. It is a negotiated
artery between two very different civilizations: Midgaard, whose
authority rests on stone law and institutional continuity, and Kiess,
whose survival depends on adaptive commerce and hard-edged logistical
pragmatism. The road persists because neither model can survive alone.

Its modern form overlays at least four historical strata: a pre-city
migration track, a formalized stone route with mile markers and
drainage cuts, a war-era military supply corridor, and a post-war
mercantile spine. Each power repaired what it needed and ignored what
did not serve immediate survival.

On the eastern half, Midgaard's imprint is carved in stone: gray-
purple ash-mortar paving from the Lantern Reforms, patrol relays,
checkpoint oath recitations, and the Three Civic Oaths recited by
wardens at every shift change. Boundary sigils are repainted even
when manpower prevents full repairs, because the Oath of Stone
requires visible evidence of maintained jurisdiction.

On the western half, Kiess convoy marshals manage actual flow
through convoy compacts -- shared liability pools that distribute
losses across all participants. A marshal can delay departures during
threat spikes, reroute convoys through the Greenveil Spur, and
authorize emergency payments to independent wayfolk for guide services.

The central Crossroads is the corridor's political heart, where
charter boundaries blur and independent actors arbitrage disagreement.
Violence spikes whenever one side attempts unilateral control. Shared
governance reduces bloodshed but increases corruption.

Along its route stands the Violet Eclipse Cathedral, an institution
whose procurement ledgers and binding archives add an unsettling
dimension to the road's layered history.

Kiess was built on the ruins of Evermeet, the fortified city that
once anchored the road's western end. When Evermeet fell, Kiess rose
on its foundations with an explicit founding clause: no sealed warrant
from a predecessor authority shall bind a Kiess citizen -- a direct
repudiation of institutional abuses committed along the road's
eastern half.

Where Midgaard asks "Who has lawful right to command?" Kiess asks
"What keeps goods and people alive to arrive tomorrow?" The road's
identity is built from that unresolved argument.

