The Roc Road: Western Corridor Governance Report

Bureau of Western Routes, Patrol and Maintenance Division
Filed under: Joint Corridor, Kiess Relations, Crossroads Administration

The Roc Road is Midgaard's western artery, and our half is
maintained to standard. Every warden recites the Three Civic
Oaths at shift change. Every checkpoint conducts oath recitations
per the Oath of the Counted Step. Gray-purple ash-mortar paving
from the Lantern Reforms still bears weight because maintenance
clerks authorize resurfacing on a seven-year cycle, documented in
paving ledger, western drawer, volumes one through forty-six.

Boundary sigils are repainted even when manpower prevents full
repairs, because the Oath of Stone requires visible jurisdiction.
This is not vanity. This is legibility. A road that cannot be
read cannot be governed. Our wardens understand this. Kiess does not.

Kiess's western half operates through convoy compacts -- shared
liability pools distributing losses across participants. A marshal
can delay departures, reroute through the Greenveil Spur, authorize
emergency payments to wayfolk. This is pragmatic. Our Bureau
acknowledges its effectiveness. But it is ideologically concerning.

Where Midgaard asks "Who has lawful right to command?" Kiess asks
"What keeps goods and people alive tomorrow?" Their founding
clause -- no sealed warrant from a predecessor shall bind a Kiess
citizen -- directly repudiates institutional continuity. Our
Continuity faction calls this civilizational negligence. Our
Reckoning faction notes Kiess repudiated those warrants because
we issued some of them.

The central Crossroads is the governance challenge. Charter
boundaries blur. Violence spikes under unilateral control attempts.
The Joint Oversight Committee has not achieved quorum in four
consecutive sessions. Shared governance reduces bloodshed but
increases forms filed under "disputed jurisdiction, pending."

The Violet Eclipse Cathedral stands along the route; its ledgers
are classified restricted review, tribunal authorization required.

Four historical strata underlie the road: migration track, stone
route, military corridor, mercantile spine. Our Bureau maintains all
four layers. Kiess maintains whichever is currently profitable.

The Roc Road proves two incompatible philosophies can share a
corridor -- and that sharing a corridor is not agreeing on its
purpose. Our paving holds. Our oaths are spoken. Whether that is
enough depends on from which end of the road one asks.
