The Roc Road -- As Kowloon Sees It

Courier Lantern Office, Western Intelligence Summary

The Roc Road connects Midgaard to Kiess. It does not connect
to Kowloon. This defines our entire relationship with the corridor:
we watch it, we price its disruptions, and we do not depend on it.

The Road is a negotiated artery between two civilizations we trade
with but do not belong to. Midgaard governs by stone law. Kiess
governs by adaptive commerce. The Harbor Syndics note with detachment:
we survive because we face the sea, not because we built a road
to a rival.

On Midgaard's half, stone paving, patrol relays, and the Three
Civic Oaths recited at every shift change. The Wardens of Iron
note: painted boundary sigils do not stop ash, flood, or famine.
On Kiess's half, convoy marshals manage flow through shared liability
pools. The Harbor Syndics recognize this -- risk distribution is
harbor doctrine by another name.

The central Crossroads is the corridor's political heart. The
Jade Magistracy tracks its instability because Crossroads disruption
affects goods prices continent-wide. When Midgaard and Kiess fight
over the center, luxury goods arrive through our Tide Gate by sea
instead. We do not wish for war on the Roc Road, but we price its
interruptions carefully.

The Violet Eclipse Cathedral along the route troubles the Temple
Circle. Procurement ledgers and binding archives suggest souls treated
as administrative material. The Temple Circle's doctrine: the dead
are named, honored, released -- not bound into archives.

Kiess was built on Evermeet's ruins, with a founding clause that
no sealed warrant from a predecessor binds a Kiess citizen. Kowloon's
Neon Covenant carries a similar refusal -- but where Kiess
repudiates sealed warrants with rhetoric, we repudiate them with
phosphorescent ink: material guarantee against forgery in darkness.

The Road asks: "Who has lawful right to command?" versus "What
keeps people alive?" Kowloon's answer is neither. We ask: "Who
keeps the lanterns lit?" Authority that does not maintain
infrastructure is performance. The Roc Road performs. We work.

The Courier Lantern Office files it under external disruption
risk: relevant to pricing, irrelevant to survival. The Roc Road is
someone else's argument. We watch it the way a harbor watches a
distant storm -- noting direction, calculating arrival, checking
our own moorings.
