The Roc Road: Two Cities Arguing Over the Best Leash

From the Garden Ledger, Diplomatic Observation File
Annotated by the Ember Warden Border Watch

The Roc Road runs between Midgaard and Kiess. One governs
by stone law. The other by adaptive commerce. Between them, a road
of layered arguments about the proper way to control passage.
Neither has asked whether control is necessary.

On the eastern half, Midgaard carves its imprint in stone: patrol
relays, checkpoint oath recitations, the Three Civic Oaths at
every shift change. Boundary sigils repainted even when manpower
prevents repairs, because the Oath of Stone requires visible
jurisdiction. The appearance of governance matters more than
the reality of care.

On the western half, Kiess convoy marshals manage flow through
shared liability pools. More practical, but no less controlling.
The marshal decides who moves and when. Kiess is honest about
calling it logistics rather than law.

The Crossroads in the center is where the argument bleeds.
Charter boundaries blur. Violence spikes when either side reaches
for unilateral control.

The Garden Ledger Clerks study the Roc Road the way healers study
illness. Midgaard asks: "Who has lawful right to command?"
Kiess asks: "What keeps goods alive to arrive tomorrow?"
Rakuen asks the question neither will consider: "What if nobody
needs to command at all?"

Kiess was built on the ruins of Evermeet, with a founding clause:
no sealed warrant from a predecessor shall bind a citizen. The Bloom
Pavilion respects this -- the closest any city has come to Rakuen's
own rejection of inherited obligation. But Kiess replaced warrants
with contracts, and contracts are warrants with better
marketing.

Rakuen has no road like this. We have the Garden Walk, where
stewards rotate and no one posts a sentry because the walk belongs
to everyone. When Midgaard's resettlement convoys brought displaced
families south during the containment era, those families arrived
along roads governed by oaths and liability pools -- and arrived
exhausted, every mile having cost them a toll or a stamp.

We offered them the Garden Walk. No oath required. No stamp demanded.
Just a path, and someone at the end with water.

That is the difference the Roc Road cannot teach, because neither
city at its ends believes a road can exist without a ledger.
