The Roc Road -- Ledger House Long-Distance Price Analysis

The Ledger Houses track the Roc Road the way a harbor pilot
tracks a distant storm: it is not our water, but what happens
there determines what arrives at our docks and at what price.

The Midgaard-Kiess corridor is the continent's other major trade
artery. Goods moving west-to-east feed into oasis corridors, cross
the desert, and reach the Saltglass Reach. By the time they
arrive at our counters, they have been taxed and re-documented
multiple times. But the price still reflects Roc Road conditions
months earlier.

When the central Crossroads destabilizes -- and it does, whenever
one side attempts unilateral control -- our commodity prices spike
within two seasons. The Sand-Sea Carters' Guild tracks this
precisely. Crossroads violence in spring means expensive iron at
our docks by autumn.

Midgaard's stone-law approach to the eastern half -- patrol relays,
checkpoint oaths, boundary sigils repainted even when manpower fails
-- is governance by visible assertion. Our Harbor Wardens understand
the impulse. But assertion without enforcement is theater, and
theater does not keep convoys safe.

Kiess convoy marshals practice shared liability pools that
distribute losses across participants. Our Ledger Houses recognize
this as maritime risk doctrine applied to land. Kiess is doing
a version of what our Shoreward Conversion does: translating
unpredictable hazard into distributable cost. We could work with
Kiess. We understand their language.

The Violet Eclipse Cathedral concerns our Quarantine Ledger. Its
procurement ledgers suggest artifact handling without proper
attestation. Cathedral-origin goods receive automatic amber-seal
classification at our docks.

Kiess was built on the ruins of Evermeet, and its founding clause
-- no sealed warrant from a predecessor shall bind a Kiess citizen
-- is a principle the Shrine of the First Claw respects. Dead
institutions cannot hold debts. Mafdet agrees with Kiess on this
point, even if we arrive at it from different directions.

Where Midgaard asks who has lawful right to command, and Kiess asks
what keeps goods and people alive, Mafdet asks a third question:
can you attest to what you are carrying? The Roc Road's unresolved
argument arrives at our harbor as cargo. We classify the cargo
and let the manifest speak.

